nderstand the historical processes central to American economic development, Enterprising America brings together contributors who address the economic behavior of American firms and financial institutions—and the associated legal institutions that shaped their behavior—throughout the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries. Collectively, the contributions provide an account of the ways in which businesses, banks, and credit markets promoted America’s extraordinary economic growth. Among the topics that emerge are the rise of incorporation and its connection to factory production in manufacturing, the organization and operation of large cotton plantations in comparison with factories, the regulation and governance of banks, the transportation revolution’s influence on bank stability and survival, and the emergence of long-distance credit in the context of an economy that was growing rapidly and becoming increasingly integrated across space.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBank loanszUnited StatesxHistoryvCongresses. 0aBusiness enterpriseszUnited StatesxFinancexHistoryvCongresses. 0aBusiness enterpriseszUnited StatesxHistoryvCongresses. 0aCommercial creditzUnited StatesxHistoryvCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aBankruptcy.  aBanks.  aGovernance.  aGrowth.  aIncorporation.  aManufacturing.  aPlantations.  aScale economies.1 aAtack, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBodenhorn, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, William J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, William J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHansen, Mary Eschelbach, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilt, Er